
Here are links to information on best-practice for data-management for research data:

A blog-post by Brian McGill (macroecologist, ecoinformatician) on the 10 commandments for good data-management:
https://dynamicecology.wordpress.com/2016/08/22/ten-commandments-for-good-data-management/
https://dynamicecology.wordpress.com/2016/08/23/sample-r-code-for-yesterdays-10-commandments-post/

Borer. E.T, et. al. 2009. Some simple guidelines for effective data management.
https://esajournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1890/0012-9623-90.2.205

British Ecological Society, Guide to Data Management in Ecology and Evolution.
https://www.britishecologicalsociety.org/wp-content/uploads/Publ_Data-Management-Booklet.pdf

Wilson. G. et. al. 2017. Good enough practices in scientific computing.
https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1005510

Stewart-Lowndes, J.S. et. al. 2017. Our path to better science in less time using open data science tools. 
https://www.nature.com/articles/s41559-017-0160

Hampton, S.E. et al. 2017. Skills and knowledge for data-intensive environmental research.
https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/67/6/546/3784601


